headline: Boeing pushes 777X jet deliveries to 2027 amid certification delays
summary: Boeing reported mixed third-quarter results on Wednesday, as higher aircraft deliveries and a growing backlog of orders were offset by continued certification delays for its 777X jets.  CEO Kelly Ortberg said the first delivery of Boeing's next generation of long-haul, wide-body jets is now expected in 2027 instead of 2026, resulting in a $4.9 billion charge in the quarter through September.  Ortberg said Boeing was making progress on stabilizing its production.

headline: Stock Market Today: Dow Falls As Powell Says December Cut Not Certain; Nvidia Higher (Live Coverage)
summary: The Dow Jones Industrial Average and other stock indexes turned lower Wednesday afternoon as Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell cast doubt on whether policymakers are locked in for another rate cut this year after November's reduction.  Stocks were higher after the Fed cut its key rate by 25 basis points but drifted downward during Powell's afternoon press conference.  The Dow fell 0.4% after briefly touching the 48,000 level for the first time.

headline: Boeing takes near $5 billion hit on 777X program
summary: STORY: Boeing reported a charge of nearly $5 billion related to delays in its 777X jet program on Wednesday.Despite progress on the 737 MAX, the planemaker continues to face setbacks with its 777X program.It said the first delivery of the model has been pushed to early 2027.The aircraft was originally marked for delivery five years ago.Last month, CEO Kelly Ortberg said the company was behind schedule in certifying the jet.Adding that a "mountain of work" needed to be done.Boeing cautiously ramped up monthly output of its 737 MAX this year.Earlier this month, the company received long-awaited approval from U.S. regulators to increase 737 MAX production to 42 jets per month.It eased a cap of 38 that had been in place since last year.That cap was imposed following a mid-air panel blowout on a nearly new aircraft.Deliveries are closely watched by Wall Street as planemakers often receive the bulk of their payments upon handing over the jets to customers.Making deliveries a key indicator of revenue and cash flow.

headline: Boeing CEO is doing all 'the right things': Analyst talks outlook
summary: Boeing (BA) may have topped third quarter revenue ($23.27 billion vs. expectations of $22.29 billion) and free cash flow estimates ( negative $238 million vs. expectations of negative $884.1 million), this was all overshadowed by a $4.9 billion charge tied to the delay in its 777X jet certification. The aircraft manufacturer also posted a much wider-than-expected loss for the quarter (a loss of $7.47 per share vs. expectations of $4.44). Gabelli Funds Portfolio Manager Tony Bancroft — who oversees the Gabelli Commercial Aerospace and Defense ETF (GCAD), which includes holdings in Boeing — expands upon his positive outlook for Boeing under CEO Kelly Ortberg's leadership.
